reviewText: It is true that this movie has a confused ending.  In fact there is no resolution at the end of this movie and I think too many people expect their movies to be neatly designed following a perfect formula.  This movie does not follow the typical formula.  It it much more like real life; just a series of events without much understanding with characters trying to get through it alive.  One of my biggest complaints about Hollywood movies is that they always follow the typical and predictable structure and formula; this movie completely does not, therefore I enjoyed this movie.  However, I think most people will not enjoy not having a nice tidy formulated movie with an ending that answers all the questions and wraps up the experience and resolves it.

reviewText: Being in the Army, I always hate movies which feature the military but give it the "Hollywood" treatment which renders it completely unrealistic.  However, I can see that The Objective hews as close to actual Army operations and tactics as I have seen in a movie.  Everything is authentic, from how they are dressed to the equipment they use to how they speak on the radio.  I give it 5 stars just for that.As for the movie itself, it follows a CIA agent and team of Special Forces soldiers (an "A-team" or Detachment Alpha) as they search supposedly for an important contact.  However, as the movie progresses the truth is revealed.  This movie is great because there is tension at many different levels, including between the CIA agent and the Special Forces team.I thought the ending was a little weak, but otherwise I'd highly recommend this movie to anyone!

reviewText: I love mixed genre movies, especially military / horror films. Movies like DEATHWATCH, THE BUNKER, THE OUTPOST, and BELOW are prime examples. THE OBJECTIVE takes this idea out of World War II and places the action in post-911 Afghanistan. We are taken along w/ a team of soldiers, escorting a CIA agent into the desolate mountain areas. Their mission is unclear, though we know from the beginning that it's probably much more than is first explained. THE OBJECTIVE has mystery, horror, drama, and suspense. There's also a nice atmosphere of dread and doom hanging over the entire story. Highly recommended...

reviewText: If you like sci-fi and don't mind using your intelligence, this is a really good movie. The key thing that most are missing is information regarding eastern myths/legends about the Djinn. That is really what this movie is about and why so many don't recognize what is going on. After you watch the movie, check out the reviews of the plot ([...] They will explain what you needed to know to understand. But I wouldn't read it until AFTER watching the movie first. Because the first experience should be as a western military would experience the phenomenon....that is why the director doesn't explain about the Djinn lore in the movie. It is more authentic to experience the phenomenon as we would (without understanding of it). Then you can go back and add in the lore to get more understanding of what was taking place.So, few movies today offer such an intelligent experience of unknown phenomenon. Which is why so many movie viewers are confused by this movie. Audiences have to have their hand held and be led through everything, have everything explained to them, etc. Instead this movie just gives you the experience of the story, but doesn't lead you and explain everything to you. You have to do some work on your own to understand the experience.And that is what the Objective is...and experience and a thoughtful one at that. Very well done, acting was good, and the military procedures for a spec ops team was done well, the lore was translated well (though not explained), etc.

reviewText: The Objective starts out with a CIA operative going to Afghanistan to recruit a small, highly trained group of military personnel for a clandestine mission, to make contact with a pro-American Mullah in order to get his pro-American statement as part of the psychological war strategy.  However, as this elite military force enters the point of no return in the Afghan wilderness, the danger mounts and the facts don't add up.  What starts as the typical and somewhat anticipated kind of danger they expect to encounter evolves into stranger and stranger phenomenon.  The men begin to question the stated objective as the team's nerves begin to fray and interpersonal tension mounts.The quality of the film is good.  The acting is good and the film definitely kept my interest as the intensity and mystery kept increasing as the film progressed.  As far as I can tell, not being ex-military myself, the armaments, outfits, and behavior seem authentic enough, although a veteran might see holes in the authenticity that I can't.The problem with The Objective is that the strange phenomenon the team encounters, that provides the powerful undercurrent of mystery and suspense, becomes too bizarre.  As the viewer, along with the team, tries to figure out what could be the source of the phenomenon, one is forced rule out various hypotheses.  One option is that it is an ancient and highly advanced alien with a raging antisocial personality disorder, based on the sadistic, malicious nature of whatever is behind the phenomenon.  Ultimately, the best fit for an explanation considering the phenomena and the supposed intent of inflicting it, is that they've encountered Satan, himself!  This is probably not what the writers intended, however.  And so, it leaves one wondering, exactly what was the writers' Objective?
summary: The Objective, That is the Question

reviewText: During the movie one of the characters asks another, "what just happened?" when there is an unexplained event. My feeling as the movie ended just happened to exactly reflect that question, what just happened. I watched the movie because I'm a science fiction fan and thought the storyline sounded interesting.About 15 minutes into the movie I was still waiting for something to happen sufficient to justify my continuing to watch and told my wife I would give it 15 more minutes and if nothing happened after that I would give up on the movie. Well, things started to happen so I continued to watch it.The first half of the movie is strictly war movie stuff of marginal interest but then things do start to happen and we begin to get some action in the story. It seems as if we were well into the second half of the movie before the first sci-fi sort of things started to happen. My wife had come into the room and was watching it with me and up until then had accepted it as a war type movie but then asked me if this was a science fiction movie. I told her I wasn't sure because up to that point there had been no dialog or action to suggest sci-fi.After one gets into the second half the science fiction element comes to the front and takes center stage all the way to the end. The end does not answer any questions and left me wondering "what just happened?" If you are a science fiction fan you may want to watch this movie but don't expect any definitive answers to the big question posed by the movie. I would suggest you view it before you buy it; I will probably not watch it again.

reviewText: I found this movie very interesting. I wouldn't quite call it a true horror movie but more of a morphing of a black-ops/science fiction/middle eastern "voodoo" movie. If nothing else, the movie is certainly unique.The acting was superb and at times the tension was almost palpable. The only problem I had with the film was that the main characters secret agent type mission was never properly explained. What had happened in the past? What initiated the deployment of the troops supporting the government agent? Apparently whatever had happened in the recent past, apparently noticed by a strange "heat signature" or the like, had happened throughout history....can't say why without spoiling things.....but though the movie left the viewer wondering exactly what he had just watched, and also left open the meaning of the mission, and exactly what led to the mission being currently held at all much less any reason for deploying apparently combat hardened vets on the "mission"..was simply not explained.What occurred in the desert during this movie was still sufficiently presented in a fashion that made for a very interesting movie and one that I had to watch twice to try to see if I had missed something......which I either did or "it" was never there.I don't really know why I liked this movie but after viewing it twice I certainly did. Certainly worth a rental.....or a used purchase from an Amazon dealer. Good movie for some reason that again I simply cannot explain.

reviewText: Daniel Myrick, one of the directors of the Blair Witch Project, spins the Blair Witch storyline a bit and comes up with this nifty other-worldly thriller. Like Blair Witch, he strands a group of people, in this case a special ops force, in a hostile environment and sets a supernatural agent upon them.These special ops dudes, headed by a CIA operative, are in search of, what we're told, may be nuclear weapons in Afghanistan. He gives his men some more benign story but they know something's up. Even with the help of a local guide, they become lost. Is it because all their high-tech gear ceases to function or has the terrain actually changed.Soon they are set upon by an enemy and, one by one, they are picked off or choose to off themselves. Mr. CIA is filming all of this with an infra-red camera and uplinking it home via infra-red. He sees things through the camera his men cannot see and finally he spills the beans to the one remaining soldier. He is trying to verify, for the CIA, the existence of Vimanas which seem to be an other-worldly force that may have been around even before Alexander the Great's conquests. They may be the ultimate weapon.As I mentioned, it's a remake of Blair Witch but with a larger budget and scope. Myrick even uses a re-occurring icon not dissimilar to the one used in Blair Witch. This is a good, solid undertaking with a mid-sized budget. The story is good. The acting is adequate and the directing is solid. As another reviewer noted, this shows you don't need truckloads of money and huge stars to make a good movie. Granted, had this had some known names, it would have gotten better backing and distribution but that's the business, not the art. If you're at all disposed to this kind of film, this is well worth your time and money.I will argue the ending. It's very brief (one shot held for a few seconds) and I'm not certain what Myrick was trying to convey. But by that time the movie was over and I was pretty much satisfied so I won't lean on that too heavily.

reviewText: I noticed some bad reviews and puffed-up reviews on here. This is a movie about a small Special Ops team. For those who don't understand this, this is very much what it's like. The operative word here is 'isolation.' Special Ops groups are usually dropped in alone and operate alone. SO soldiers are highly trained to deal with the rigors of isolation and operating on their own, usually in enemy territory. They are pretty much considered expendable. It is difficult to write a screenplay about something like this because it would concern mostly interaction among strongly egoed and forceful men who have to work together. I think they did OK in this right. The CIA agent keeps the Team in the dark as to the objective (which is common). And we don't really learn what it's all about until the end, when the aliens are introduced. If you don't understand how this kind of thing works, the film would be boring to you. It's a subtle film, built on character interaction, where accomplishing the mission is the foremost impetus. More of a film for ex-military, who would appreciate it.

reviewText: The mission objective is vague, and left more or less up in the air until almost the end, what one would call the climax of the story. Bermuda Triangle stories end the same way.  X-Files had stories end this way.  Some sequences reminded me of Carlos Castaneda's works, too.  Our imaginations should be spurred into action by this, but instead I see reviews of people who's imaginations are dead, or non existent.  This story ends just as it should, and it was presented appropriately.  In life, not everything gets explained, and we certainly don't have all the answers.

reviewText: This movie flirts with the idea that the old notions of the magical Djinn are based in truth, and that out in the deserts of the Middle East they are still to be found.I have a soft spot for movies about small bands of soldiers, heading off into the boondocks where they will face the unknown in ways they could never have imagined.  Outpost, Predator, Aliens, Dog Soldiers...  These are all films that fit into that niche. So does The Objective.The Objective is riddled with mythological motifs that will fly over the head of most people.  If you've ever read the substantial works of Joseph Campbell and liked them (Hero with a Thousand Faces, The Masks of God series, etc.,) then this film will really appeal to you.  If you have no idea what the books I just mentioned are all about, then you probably have very little interest in comparative mythology, and this movie might not be your cup of tea.  Without the mythological references, The Objective might just seem like a bunch of things that don't make much sense, and in the end feel unsatisfying.If you like mythology, definitely give this one a look.  If you don't know much about it, you should look anyway, and maybe it will broaden your horizons.  If your idea of an imaginative romp is Law and Order, leave this one alone.
summary: If you liked Outpost, you'll like The Objective

reviewText: I got this movie for $4.00 at Blockbuster so I had very low expectations of it. What a pleasant surprise it was. The story of a CIA operative who takes a special forces team into Afghanistan with him to look for a mysterious 'thing' that might be a nuclear weapon. Normally I don't go for the horror/sci-fi/war type film but this movie blew me away. The movie has tons of action with the team of men encountering real 'bad guys'as well as forces they can't explain out to do them in. As the movie unfolds and we find out what the supposed nuclear device really is, you might not be impressed but I was and again I'm not a huge sci-fi fan. The special forces troops and the CIA agent are all totally believable and the ending was shocking but satisfying. This film reminded me a bit of 'Jacobs Ladder' so if your a fan of that Tim Robbins film you should like this.

reviewText: This is a combo war/UFO/sci fi/mythological weirdness movie that never quite gets off the ground. Most of the movie involves a team of Special Forces soldiers, an Afghan guide, and a secretive CIA agent hoofing it through the desert to find a holy man and get to a mysterious hot spot that could be nuclear or could be something else more mystical.  In the process, bizarre things happen and in the end (slight spoiler alert), the CIA guy is hooked up and levitating.  So I'm thinking that maybe he was the object of a government experiment and the whole journey was a drug-induced dream.  Just a wild guess, though.

reviewText: Some reviewers complain that the ending is weird and it doesn't tie up loose ends.  Others complain that the pacing is slow and it doesn't go anywhere.  They have a point.  But, then, the same point can be made about "2001: A Space Odyssey," unquestionably a great movie in any genre.  It too is slow-paced with little action but the tension builds throughout, right up to the weird psychedelic ending.  Light sabers and mindless action aren't required.  "The Objective" isn't on a par with "2001," not by a long shot, but it is a good, thought-provoking science fiction flick. It's slow-paced and the tension builds gradually until it explodes in truly mind-blowing weirdness at the end.  I like it.  I like the scenes in the desolate mountains of Afghanistan (actually Morocco), and it had the feel of a real mission by special forces in that war-torn country.  Except for the actor playing the CIA agent who seemed ill-suited to the role, the other actors were spot on.
summary: Weird, Provocative and Worth a Look

reviewText: From the co-director of "The Blair Witch Project" and the director of "Altered" comes this less impressive peice.  It appears that director, Daniel Myrick might have bit off more than he could chew on this one.  The premise is intriguing enough, but half way into it, the plot appears muddled.  A lot of arguing amongst the men in the cast and nobody has a lot to say.  In fact, some of the dialogue is cringe inducing.  "The Objective" is no where near as eerie or interesting as "Blair Witch" and there is no fun to be found as in Myrick's previous effort "Altered," which I highly recommend.  Production values are decent, but effects are cheesy at times.  I'm wondering if budget problems in the end did not hamper this production.  Ashame, because I was looking forward to it.  Iteresting enough, if you want to see how Myrick is growing as a director, only because of what he is suggesting in his vision.  Given a little more time with script and a better effects budget the film might have kept his track record going.

reviewText: This little known film mixes with some success the SF and horror with a war movie. In a desolate, isolated region of southern Afghanistan an American patrol, which includes Special Forces soldiers, a CIA operative and an Afghan scout, looks for an elusive but influent cleric, who lives in a hermitage somewhere in the mountains. But soon after the beginning of the mission, strange things begin to happen...Made by the director Daniel Myrick, who earlier became famous with "Blair Witch Project", this film is pretty weird and reminded me of some of the most surrealistic moments in "X-Files" - and in fact by simply looking at the cover you will notice that some UFO-like floating lights will be included... Actors were unknown to me, but they acted well. There is some limited action, but the gunfights are REALLY not the point in this film. The vision of Afghan mountains is well done - it is really not a place I would like to find myself, even without the taliban barbarians around. Simple Afghan villagers are portrayed with respect and sympathy, as is the old hermit-cleric. Questions and mysteries pile up and, as in "Blair Witch Project", they will not be fully answered. Butcher bill is heavy and some of the death moments are pretty graphic. Finally, the general mood of the film is somehow depressing...Important precision - this is NOT a "found video" film, like "Blair Witch Project" or "Cloverfield" were. Here the visual approach is more classic.I rather liked this film. It is not as good as "Blair Witch Project", but it has something in it. Not something to watch on a date or on a romantic evening - rather recommened for a late night, beer+pop corn, "wife and kids are asleep and I have a little moment for myself" viewing. Enjoy!
summary: "X-Files" goes to war in Afghanistan and meets "Blair Witch Project"

reviewText: The Objective is supposedly about a Special Forces team sent on a mysterious mission to Afghanistan to investigate what might or might not be a UFO.  But let's be honest: director Daniel Myrick had access to film in a desert/mountainous region and wanted to make a movie out of it.Undercover CIA agent Benjamin Keynes (Jonas Ball) narrates in hushed whispers this doomed mission, which may or may not be a suicide run to discover a terrorist known only as Muhammad.  Unless of course it's THAT Muhammad, in which case discovering him would be a pretty big deal since, you know, he's a divine prophet.Thrown into the mix are Vimanas, the ancient Indian flying saucers, ghostly Arabs in black garb, and many, many blurry shots taken by an infrared camera. The best scene is the arrival of the UFOs, which chant calls to prayer, and the moment when our lone hero launches a signal flare only to discover he's already launched/is currently launching/will launch thousands more as he approaches a singularity. But those trippy moments are all too brief.This is not a good film.  Big on ideas, short on a coherent plot, when The Objective does standard combat ops its pitch perfect; when it tries to do just about anything else it's an inchoate mess of swear words, blurry camera angles, and bright red gore props. We never find out what the "aliens" want, what the original mission was, or why the audience has to suffer through over an hour of men trudging through the desert before we get an explanation as to why they're there. The Objective might have a clear goal, but it's not sharing it with anybody.

reviewText: Directed by Blair Witch Project co-creator Daniel Myrick, The Objective concerns a group of soldiers led by a CIA agent (Jonas Ball) two months after 9/11, on a mission in Afghanistan to locate a man.  It isn't long however before the soldiers figure out this isn't just any normal location mission.  I really don't want to give too much away here, other than to say that what develops in The Objective is a very intelligent, engaging, and thought provoking thriller that is often ambiguous (particularly its ending), and even more so tension filled throughout.  It would also be easy for some to label The Objective under the horror genre, but with what all Myrick injects into the film, it becomes slightly elevated compared to the typical horror conventions that the film could have easily degraded towards.  All in all, you won't see many films like The Objective, and it isn't a film for everyone, but it definitely deserves attention regardless, as it isn't often that a film like this and this well-made comes along.

reviewText: Overall, not a bad movie, though it had some issues, I give it marks in the "different" category and being somewhat true to a military scenario.The story follows a CIA agent who is sent to Afghanistan to search for a heat signature from an unknown source (wink).  He gathers a U.S. Army Special Forces Team to assist him, and tells them that he's looking for an old informant, which sends them on sort of a goose chase into the mountains.It doesn't have a lot of action (things being blown up and stuff) but it does have a very different story that is somewhat intriguing, paired with a ground of interesting characters (somewhat), made me want to see it to the end.Now, it could have done with more suspense, and better pacing (gets a little slow at times), more work on the characters (more personality coming through the dialogue and better empathy for them, a stronger hero), and a stronger story (more at stake for the hero, greater tension, etc). reviewText: This movie will soar over most American heads.This is the heaviest movie I have seen in years, and that it is made in the US is impressive.Besides the references to Djinn and spirituality, there are plenty of goods and inconsistencies which play in either direction. Also would like to see some action follow-up, but it would probably not be as good since we need a bit of mystery to it.Key words in the film, include Keynes saying how he was the messenger. Altho he refered to the CIA here, he obviously became a spiritual messenger in the end thru making contact, and surviving--albeit obviously transformed. Now that he can levitate, radiate heat (or radiation?), speak the mysterious language of the Eastern mystics, and can probably do things no one else on earth can do, they have him locked away in a lab to study. If you would like to see a few tantalizing reenactments of well worn UFO stories set in the unusual and reassuring context of a movie about a military band of brothers in peril Objective might work for you. reviewText: I found most of the story interesting, the characters believable, and mission mysterious enough to keep me watching until the end. It doesn't rely on special effects to make the story, which is refreshing in an era when EPM (Explosions Per Minute) seem to drive the success of too many movies. I'm a die hard sci-fi fan and seeing the genre become more popular to general audiences has been a blessing and a curse; more movies in the genre are produced, but the stories are often flimsy. I give this one kudos for having a plot that was engaging.Like others I'm not sure what to make of the ending. I'm fine with endings that don't necessarily resolve the conflict in the story arc -in fact I often prefer that as it generally seems more realistic than one that knits all the loose end and tosses a happy ending out to get to it and roll the credits - but something about this left me dissatisfied. It gave me the sense that there needed to be 10 more minutes of story. It was more like the mysterious ending wasn't quite long enough to make it compelling. To use a very controversial ending as a means of explaining this, I'll refer to the Sopranos. We didn't get any specific answers, but the loose-ends-ending gave enough information for viewers to speculate about what could have happened after the series officially ended. Love or hate the ending of the Sopranos, the writers gave fans enough to argue about for years. This movie didn't achieve even that. Even so, I don't think it was a waste of my viewing time.If you like a story driven sci-fi plot, it's worth watching as long as you are also prepared for the extremely vague ending.
summary: Falls slightly short of really good
